definition.value: The L-enantiomer of glyceraldehyde.
A phenylacetaldehyde in which the 3 and 4 positions of the phenyl group are substituted by hydroxy groups.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of all-cis-icosa-8,11,14-trienoic acid.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pyruvic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 3,5-dinitro-4-hydroxyphenyl group.
A nitrile that is acetonitrile where one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 2-methylphenyl group.
A member of the class of aminopyrimidines that is 4,6-diaminopyrimidine bearing an additional formamido substituent at position 5. A DNA lesion formed when DNA exposed to ionising radiation.
A nitroso compound that is the nitroso derivative of benzene; a diamagnetic hybrid of singlet O2 and azobenzene.
An  inositol that is cyclohexane-1,2,3,4,5,6-hexol having a (1R,2R,3r,4R,5S,6r)-configuration.
A UDP-sugar having 2-deoxyglucose as the sugar component.
An ethoxybenzoic acid carrying an ethoxy substituent at position 3.
A nitrile that is hydrogen cyanide in which the hydrogen has been replaced by a phenyl group.
A 4-hydroxy-D-proline in which the hydroxy group at position 4 has S-configuration.
An O-acyl carbohydrate that is beta-D-glucose carrying sinapoyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions.
A glycosyloxyflavone that is luteolin substituted by a beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A methylbenzyl alcohol that is toluene in which one of the meta hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxymethyl group.
A 9-octadecenoic acid and the trans-isomer of oleic acid.
An N-sulfonylurea that consists of 1-butylurea having a tosyl group attached at the 3-position.
The (R)-enantiomer of linalool.

A complex glycopeptide from Streptomyces orientalis. It inhibits a specific step in the synthesis of the peptidoglycan layer in the Gram-positive bacteria Staphylococcus aureus and Clostridium difficile.
A medium-chain unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of cis,cis-dodeca-3,6-dienoic acid.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid.
An organic thiophosphate that is the diethyl ester of phosphorothioic O,O,O-acid.
An N-acetyl-D-glucosamine having beta-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A macromolecule consisting of 10-formyltetrahydrofolic acid with an arbitrary number of glutamate residues attached as a polypeptide to the single existent one.
A 3-oxoacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxy-6-oxocyclohexane-1-carboxylic acid.
A D-fructofuranose 1,6-bisphosphate with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.

A pyrazolopyrazole that is 6,7-dihydro-1H,5H-pyrazolo[1,2-a]pyrazole-3-carboxylic acid which has been substituted at positions 2, 5 and 6 by methylsulfonyl, oxo, and amino groups, respectively, and in which the amino group has been condensed with the carboxy group of (2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)(oxo)acetic acid, the oxo group of which has been converted to the corresponding oxime O-allyl ether.
A chloroamino acid that is L-tyrosine carrying chloro- substituents at positions C-3 and C-5 of the benzyl group.
The most important reserve polysaccharide found in plants. It is a glucan consisting of amylose and amylopectin.
A monomethoxyflavone that is the 8-O-methyl derivative of gossypetin .
